Starting out in the UK research commu- nity, from around 2013, through discussions initiated by the Software Sustainability Institute (https://software.ac.uk), groups focusing on de- veloping sustainable, maintainable, robust research software have been set up at many institutions.

Communities such as the DevLOG network (http://devlog.cnrs.fr/) in France have existed for some time, providing support and skills development opportunities to individuals undertaking software-related work.

These include Germany (deRSE ‚Äì https://www.de-rse.org), the Nether- lands (NL-RSE ‚Äì https://nl-rse.org/), the Nordic region (Nordic-RSE ‚Äì http://nordic-rse.org/), the US (US-RSE ‚Äì https://us-rse.org/) and Aus- tralia/New Zealand (RSE AU/NZ community ‚Äì https://rse-aunz.github.
The most recent development has been the creation of a professional society for RSEs: the Society of Research Software Engineering (https://society-rse.org/) in the UK.
4 (https://rslondon.ac.uk) for London and the South East of England.

An international community level is also emerging with the formation of Research Software Engineers International in 2018, after leaders of national RSE associations, groups and related initiatives from around the world came together in London for the Ô¨Årst International RSE Lead- ers Workshop, and with the launch of the Research Software Alliance (https://www.researchsoft.org/).

Other international communities such as WSSSPE ‚Äì Working Towards Sustainable Software for Science: Practice and Experiences (http://wssspe.researchcomputing.org.uk) ‚Äì bridge the core research software community and more research- focused aspects of software engineering and computing covering areas such as empirical software engineering.

According to the International Trail Running Association (ITRA, https://itra.run/ ), the largest trail running organization worldwide, trail running is a sport that takes place in a natural environment and enhances a shared sense of community among runners.

One of the most famous trail running competitions, the Western States Endurance Run ( https://www.wser.org/ ), a 161 km race with 5500 m1of elevation gain in California, was run for the Ô¨Årst time in 1974; at that time, it was only known as a horse race and a participant decided to run instead of riding his horse.

Similarly, Ultra-Trail du Mont-Blanc (UTMB, https://utmbmontblanc.com/ ), with 171 km and 10000 m of elevation gain crossing France, Italy, and Switzerland, started with only a few participants in 2003 and now manages admissions through a lottery system.

Indeed, most of the famous races, such as UTMB, Western States, Hardrock 100 ( https://hardrock100.com/ ), Lavaredo Ultra-Trail (LUT, https://www.ultratrail.it ), Tor des G√©ants (TOR, https://www.tordesgeants.it ), Marathon des Sables ( https://www.marathondessables.com/en ), and Ultra-Trail Mount Fuji ( https://www.ultratrailmtfuji.com/en/ ) are all ultra-trails.
All collected data used in this manuscript are available at a GitHub repository https://github.com/ricfog/TRAP_data .
However, we are aware of a service provided by a proprietary software, LiveTrail ( https://www.livetrail.net/ ), similar to part of the framework presented here.
On the one hand, we have made available to the public (available on GitHub https://github.com/ricfog/TRAP_data ) a data set containing race- and runner-level information recorded on the ITRA website.
